response:
The correct ratio is $\boxed{\frac{2\pi}{15\sqrt{5}}}$. The correct diagram is shown above, and it is obvious that the height and base radius of the cone are in the proportion $4:3$, which leads us to think of a 30-60-90 triangle. Let the radius of the sphere be $s$, and extend the radius of the sphere so that it reaches the boundary. Call the center point $D$ and connect it to the base so that it reaches the midpoint $M$ of the base. Then, notice that $D$ is also the center of the base of the cone. The radius of the base of the cone is 3, so $DM=3$. The height of the small cone (the cone that was cut off by the sphere, $\triangle DMB$) is then $4-s$, as shown below. [asy]
draw((0,2)..(1.5,1)..(3,0));
draw((0,0)..(1.5,-1)..(3,0),dashed);
